Plot and Inference • Show a time series plot. • Please summarize your observations of the time series plot

salesTimeSeries <- ts(salesData$sales, frequency = 12, start = c(2020,1))
plot(salesTimeSeries)

Summary of the plot: -In the given plot we can see that there’s significant increase in the sales over the years from 2020 to 2024. -Plot shows that the sales start is low level in 2020 and rise gradually and evidently fluctuate from 2023 suggesting seasonality and cyclical patterns. -Sales starts declining from around 2024.

Decomposition • Plot the decomposition of the time series.

#Using STL decomposition
decomposition_stl <- stl(salesTimeSeries,s.window ="periodic")
plot(decomposition_stl, main = 'Decomposition')

• Is the time series seasonal?

#seasonal component
plot(decomposition_stl$time.series[, "seasonal"], main="Seasonal Component")

YES, looking at the repeating patterns in seasonal component we can see that the time series is seasonal.

• Is the decomposition additive or multiplicative?

decompose <- decompose(salesTimeSeries)
decompose$type
## [1] "additive"

The consistancy in the scale of seasonal and reminder components suggests that the decompositon is additive.

• Can you think of the reason behind the high and low values in those months?

-High demand in May can be due to seasonal demand. -It can also by because of increased healthcare campaigns and promotional activities in summers -Lowest value in December can be because of the holiday seasons. - Also, as insurance policies or benefits can often reset at the start of the tear hence people might hold on to their December purchase till January.

Residual analysis: -From around 2022 onward, the residuals start to show larger fluctuations, both positive and negative. Alos, the naive model’s residuals have increasing variability and a clear seasonal pattern, especially from 2023 onward. -This suggests that the naive model has increasing difficulty accurately capturing the actual values as time progresses, possibly due to rising seasonality or trend in the data. -This histogram of the residuals shows a slight positive skew, with most residuals clustering around zero but with some higher positive values.The lack of a normal, symmetric distribution suggests the model may not fully capture all patterns in the data. - fitted vs residual graph: This graph pattern suggests that the naive model may be systematically underestimating high values and overestimating low values, indicating potential model bias. - actal vs residual: this graph shows a clear downward trend, indicating that as the actual sales increase, the residuals tend to become more negative.

Simple Moving Averages • Plot the graph for the time series. • Show the Simple Moving average of order three on the plot above in Red • Show the Simple Moving average of order six on the plot above in Blue • Show the Simple Moving average of order nine on the plot above in Green • (Bonus) show the forecast for the next 12 months using one of the simple average orders that you feel works best for time series • What are your observations of the plot as the moving average order goes up?

#Moving Avg
MAforecast1 = ma(salesTimeSeries,order=3)
MAforecast2 = ma(salesTimeSeries,order=6)
MAforecast3 = ma(salesTimeSeries,order=9)

plot(salesTimeSeries)
lines(MAforecast1, col="red")
lines(MAforecast2, col="blue")
lines(MAforecast3, col="green")

MAforecast <- ma(salesTimeSeries,12)
plot(MAforecast)
lines(MAforecast, col="purple")

This follows the upward trend from 2020 until early 2023, including seasonal variability especially after 2022. On the end of the year 2024, sales show a significant drop. The colored lines represent the various forecasting methods when the order is set to 3,6,and 9. Each closely follows the actual data through late 2023, where they started to diverge in different directions, indicative of uncertainty about future projections.

Holt-Winters • Perform Holt-Winters forecast for the next 12 months for the time series. o What is the value of alpha? What does that value signify?

alpha = 0.2948

Alpha specifies the coefficient for the level smoothing in Holtwinters.

o What is the value of beta? What does that value signify? beta = 0.0894

Beta specifies the coefficient for the trend smoothing in Holtwinters.

o What is the value of gamma? What does that value signify? gamma = 1e-04

Gamma specifies the coefficient for the seasonal smoothing in Holtwinters.

o What is the value of initial states for the level, trend, and seasonality? What do these values signify? Initial states: l = 446.9245 b = 354.2206 s = -1661.38 1750.277 -1588.956 -1283.547 1035.267 -838.3166 1015.053 2130.941 124.725 -81.034 1045.168 -1648.196
